3:The recurrence kind is inferred from the period-token suffix shape in the task title. On each eligible materialize, the controller performs a **scan-and-collapse**: it lists same-slug instances, ranks them most-recent-first by a parsed period-token **ordinal**, and closes every still-open prior within a bounded **look-back** window of K instances (default 7).
5:Token shapes and firing rules are defined in the Obsidian KB page [[Per-Kind Firing Semantics for Recurring Task Schedulers]]. This document covers the scan-and-collapse contract that `bborbe/agent-task-controller` uses to implement auto-supersede.
29:When a recurring-task instance is materialized, the controller executes the following scan-and-collapse step:
41:At most **K** (the look-back bound, `SUPERSEDE_LOOKBACK`, default 7) most-recent candidates are read and evaluated. K is the **total** number of prior candidates inspected ‚ÄĒ not the number closed. If fewer than K priors exist, all are inspected. Older priors beyond the K-window are left open.
45:Each still-open (`phase: in_progress`) prior candidate is **collapsed**: the controller writes the frozen transition frontmatter fields:
57:List, read, parse, and write errors for any individual file are logged and swallowed. The scan continues to the next candidate. If the new instance's own write fails, the error is propagated (not swallowed).
61:If a prior candidate is already `status: aborted` (redelivery of the new instance), it is skipped. Re-running collapse on the same candidate set is safe.
65:This contract does not change the `bborbe/recurring-task-creator` publisher, the Schedule CRD, or the supersede output schema (the frozen transition fields above). Only the controller's scan-and-collapse logic is in scope.
